metadata.metaValue:
The read_json operator is hard-coded to handle up to 3D nested arrays at compile time. If you need support for more, you must recompile the operator. As a fallback, it will use array<any>. 

This behaviour is reflected inside this retreival operator. By default, it will assume a homogenous nested array if the depth is less than or equal to 3. This can be overridden if you have mixed types inside a 3D array or less in your JSON data by turning on the `force_array_any` option.

Therefore we must cast our intermediate array chains to the corresponding nested arrays of objects (for example, array<array<object>> for 2 intermediate array retrievals in a row) because the read_json operator will do so internally and retrieval will fail otherwise. If you have mixed arrays at intermediate levels please use the `force_array_any` option like mentioned earlier. You may also need to use this option if retrieving from objects not created by the read_json operator.
